SIMPLE: warping
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warping
<hw>Warp"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of
one who, or that which, warps.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The art or occupation of preparing warp or webs for
the weaver.</def> <rj><au>Craig.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Warping bank</b></col>, <cd>a bank of earth raised round
a field to retain water let in for the purpose of enriching land.</cd>
<au>Craig.</au> -- <col><b>Warping hook</b></col>, <cd>a hook used by
rope makers for hanging the yarn on, when warping it into hauls for
tarring.</cd> -- <col><b>Warping mill</b></col>, <cd>a machine for
warping yarn.</cd> -- <col><b>Warping penny</b></col>, <cd>money,
varying according to the length of the thread, paid to the weaver by the
spinner on laying the warp.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<au>Wright.</au> -- <col><b>Warping post</b></col>, <cd>a strong post
used in warping rope-yarn.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warp knitting</ent>⟦br⟧
